      <hedline>
        <hl1>Africa, in Close Focus</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>R Edward Lomas letter on Aug 27 article urges United States to look beyond sterotypes and consider all African nations as individual entities</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''The U.S. Keeps Looking for a Few Good Men'' (Week in Review, Aug. 27), you say American ''to African nations'' was $738 million this year. You go on to compare this figure with that of Egypt, which received about $760 million.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''The U.S. Keeps Looking for a Few Good Men'' (Week in Review, Aug. 27), you say American ''to African nations'' was $738 million this year. You go on to compare this figure with that of Egypt, which received about $760 million.</p>
        <p>Egypt is a part of Africa as much as Colombia is a part of South America. Black Africa differs within itself as much as Egypt differs from the other African countries.</p>
        <p>Though many of the black African countries have serious problems, not all black African countries are hopelessly mired in civil war and corruption. If we could look beyond the stereotype and consider all African countries as individual entities,  much needed aid might be forthcoming.</p>
        <p>R. EDWARD LOMAS  Long Valley, N.J., Aug. 27, 2000</p>
      </block>
